 to get tax credits backdated</h2>\n\n<p>Usually, you don’t have to do anything - it happens automatically. The date they’re backdated to is shown on your award notice. </p>\n\n<h2>Exceptions</h2>\n\n<p>You have to ask for your tax credits to be backdated if you get:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Income Support </li>\n  <li>Jobseeker’s Allowance (income-based) </li>\n  <li>Employment and Support Allowance (income-related) </li>\n  <li>Pension Credit </li>\n  <li>Working Tax Credit and you’re not claiming for any children </li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>To do this include a page with your claim form confirming: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>your name, address and National Insurance number </li>\n  <li>the date you started work</li>\n  <li>if you’re not in work - the date you started getting one of the benefits above </li>\n</ul>\n\n<h2>Backdating more than a month</h2>\n\n<p>Claims can be backdated by more than a month if:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>you or your child start to get a disability benefit - eg Disability Living Allowance</li>\n  <li>you start to get a sickness benefit - eg Statutory Sick Pay</li>\n  <li>you get refugee status</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You must send your claim within 1 month of qualifying for the above. The Tax Credit Office will tell you how much more you’ll get. </p>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/claim-tax-credits/what-counts-as-income","slug":"what-counts-as-income","order":5,"title":"What counts as income","body":"<p>Usually, what you&rsquo;re entitled to is based on your income for the last tax year (6 April 2011 to 5 April 2012). </p>\n\n<p>Income includes: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>work - your earnings before tax and national insurance (check your P60 or payslips) </li>\n  <li>certain benefits</li>\n  <li>money from a pension - including your state pension (if it&rsquo;s more than £300 a year) </li>\n  <li>interest on savings (if it&rsquo;s more £300 a year)</li>\n  <li>your partner&rsquo;s income - if you make a <a href=\"/claim-tax-credits/joint-claims\" title=\"Joint claims\">joi